# Import lobster data

lobster_abundance <- read_csv(here::here("data","lobster_abundance.csv"),
                              na = "-99999") %>% 
  clean_names()

Use the tidyr::uncount() function to expand a frequency variable

lobster_tidy <- lobster_abundance %>%
  tidyr::uncount(lobster_count)

Yaya! Now each lobster has its own row. This is tidy format.

Lets look at this a bunch of ways:

ggplot(data = lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color = site),
              width = 0.2,
              alpha = 0.3)
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data = lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +

              alpha = 0.3)

  geom_qq(size = 0.5) +
  facet_wrap(~site, scales = "free")

5. Parse dates for lobster observations

Notice that the existing class of the date variable is a character. Boo.

class(lobster_abundance$date)
## [1] "character"

The lubridate package (part of the tidyverse), and is built to make it easier to deal with date-time data. Here, well use lubridate::mdy() to help R understand its a date, and work with the pieces (month, day and year) more easily.

Note: were using mdy() because thats the existing format of the date column (mm/dd/yy). Check ?ymd to see all the different options based on the format of your date column. Cool.

Add a new column with mutate() that is a date using mdy():

lobster_date <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  mutate(
    date_new = lubridate::mdy(date)
  )

Check it out! The date_new column is in nice ISO date format. Lets check the class:

class(lobster_date$date_new)
## [1] "Date"

Wooooo.

Now that its in date format, we can parse it. See ?month and ?year - to get or set components of a date or date-time. So here, well use lubridate::month() and lubridate::year() to create separate columns for the month and year.

For month(), we can even automatically convert to month abbreviation with argument label = TRUE.

lobster_parse_date <- lobster_date %>% 
  mutate(obs_month = lubridate::month(date_new, label = TRUE),
         obs_year = lubridate::year(date_new))

Count lobsters by different groupings

Lets say I want to count the number of lobsters by year and month

lobster_ym <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  count(obs_year, obs_month)

# group_by + summarize + n()
lobster_summary <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  group_by(site) %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_size = mean(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_size = sd(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
    sample_n = n()
  )

Confidence intervals and t-tests

Use the t-test() function to find confidence intervals and perform t-tests

ivee_lobsters <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "IVEE") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

my_vector <- c(3, 5, 9, 15, 24)

t.test(ivee_lobsters)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  ivee_lobsters
## t = 245.23, df = 2302, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  72.99130 74.16806
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  73.57968

Two-sample t-test: Is there a significant difference in mean lobster lengths between Naples Reef and Mohawk Reef?

napl_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "NAPL") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

mohk_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "MOHK") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

mohk_napl_ttest <- t.test(napl_sample, mohk_sample)

mohk_napl_ttest
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  napl_sample and mohk_sample
## t = 19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  10.19806 12.43436
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  78.18454  66.86833

Mean lobster size differed significantly between Mohawk and Naples reefs

Maybe an easier way

lobster_2sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site %in% c("NAPL","MOHK"))

ttest_2 <- t.test(size_mm ~ site, data = lobster_2sample)

ttest_2
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  size_mm by site
## t = -19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -12.43436 -10.19806
## sample estimates:
## mean in group MOHK mean in group NAPL 
##           66.86833           78.18454
